&lt;p&gt;For a fixed non-square integer N &gt; 1, represent the set Z(√N) = {a + b√N : a, b ∈ Z} by the set Z x Z. The norm of an element (a, b) of Z x Z, denoted N(a, b), is the integer&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a&lt;sup&gt;&lt;span&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;–N * b&lt;sup&gt;&lt;span&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/sup&gt;. For each integer k, Z&lt;sub&gt;&lt;span&gt;k &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/sub&gt;denotes the k-norm class {(a, b) ∈ Z x Z : k = N(a, b)}.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For N the set V (N) = {k : Z&lt;sub&gt;&lt;span&gt;k &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/sub&gt;is nonempty} is closed under integer multiplication, suggesting an algebraic structure on the corresponding set of norm classes. Towards analyzing this suggested algebraic structure, the generating sets of these norm classes are examined. It is shown that each of these generating elements produces a structural component satisfying a well-known distribution known as Benford’s Law. Benford’s Law is&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;perpetuated, via algebraic properties of Z x Z to each norm class, as well as to&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;larger substructures of Z x Z.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In this talk we present results on these structural aspects of the quadratic integer ring Z(√N)).&lt;/p&gt;
